<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  ZarOS Font Configuration
  ========================
  Every ZarOS brand text view (boot logo, lock screen clock, home screen
  watermark, Clock app display) references @string/font_clock below instead
  of a hardcoded font name. That means installing the real Orbitron font is
  now a ONE-LINE change — no hunting through layout files required.

  STATUS: Pointed at @font/orbitron_bold below. You just need to copy the
  actual font file into place — see FINAL STEP at the bottom.

  You downloaded the VARIABLE font (Orbitron-VariableFont_wght.ttf), which
  contains every weight (100–900) in a single file controlled by a "wght"
  axis, rather than separate Bold/Regular files. Android's resource system
  expects one weight per file, so rename it on the way in:

  FINAL STEP (run on your machine, not in this chat):
    cp ~/Downloads/Orbitron/Orbitron-VariableFont_wght.ttf \
       <path-to-project>/ZarOS/app/src/main/res/font/orbitron_bold.ttf

  Android will render the variable font file at whatever weight the
  view's android:textStyle requests (the clock views already use
  android:textStyle="bold"), so no further config is needed — Android
  reads the variable font's default/bold instance automatically on API 26+,
  which matches ZarOS's minSdk.

  After copying the file, just rebuild in Android Studio. No XML changes
  needed beyond what's already set below.
-->
<resources>
    <string name="font_clock">@font/orbitron_bold</string>
</resources>
